The typical approach layers multiple configuration sources with increasing priority:

1. Default values in code
2. Configuration file (TOML/YAML/JSON)
3. Environment variables
4. Command-line arguments

Using serde + clap + dotenvy:

#[derive(Deserialize)]
struct Config {
    #[serde(default = "default_port")]
    port: u16,
    database_url: String,
    log_level: String,
}

fn default_port() -> u16 { 8080 }

fn load_config() -> Result<Config> {
    // Load .env file
    dotenvy::dotenv().ok();

    // Read from file
    let file_config = std::fs::read_to_string("config.toml")?;
    let mut config: Config = toml::from_str(&file_config)?;

    // Override with environment variables
    if let Ok(url) = std::env::var("DATABASE_URL") {
        config.database_url = url;
    }

    Ok(config)
}

The config crate provides a more automated layered approach. For simple CLIs, clap alone may suffice.
